  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The book \"Advances in Knowledge Discovery and Data Mining,\" published by Springer International Publishing in 2020, represents a significant contribution to the fields of data science and machine learning, suggesting a noteworthy scholarly uptake with 23 citations observed.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Published in 2020, \"Advances in Knowledge Discovery and Data Mining\" by Springer International Publishing has established itself as a relevant reference point in the domains of data analytics and machine learning. With a total of 23 citations recorded, the work demonstrates a solid level of scholarly uptake, indicating that it has been recognized and utilized by other researchers in the field.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Despite the absence of online discussions or community mentions on popular platforms, the book\u2019s academic footprint suggests its importance, particularly in the ongoing evolution of knowledge discovery techniques. The cited works reflect an engagement from researchers who are likely to build upon the methodologies and findings presented within its chapters.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The narrative of this book underscores the importance of rigorous scientific inquiry in data mining and knowledge discovery, which continues to shape practices across various sectors reliant on data analysis. Its reception within academic circles suggests that it has effectively catered to emerging needs and interests in the increasingly complex landscape of data-driven research.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">As data science continues to expand, works like this one serve not only as scholarly references but also as foundational texts from which new insights and methodologies can be derived. The positive citation metrics indicate a vibrant dialogue within the scholarly community related to the themes addressed in this publication, potentially paving the way for future research initiatives in the field.</p>",
